stylometry: The @RISK output shows you the mean and the standard deviation for the different order quantities you are looking at. It shows you the risk that goes with each of the possible quanities. The output also shows you the minimum and maximum for each of the quantities. When making a decision, like how many calanders to order, you want a high mean and a low standard deviation, this would be a soultion with realtivly minimal risk. You could also be looking for a risky solution that could have a very large profit, which would be a solution with the highest mean and the standard deviation could be either high or low. In general, the higher the mean the more profit the lower the standard deviation the lower the risk.
